The analogy I keep in mind: USB Mouse Standard:  x/y axis, wheel, three buttons.  Beyond that, it's custom drivers.

@Jonathan Wise alluded that these efforts are ongoing, but failure to standardize the basic and allow end users/integrators to build on that with expanded standards or expanded customization is why adoption is so low.

1) Start with the use-case, 2) define standardized interfaces to help automate integrations where needed, 3) go custom otherwise

@MParris the USB analogy is maybe more apt than you know. Part of why USB "plug and play" works is that even though there's hundreds of thousands of unique USB devices, most of them boil down to common base classes (eg: HID [HumanInterfaceDevice], MassStorage, Audio, etc...)
These have been standardized (https://www.usb.org/defined-class-codes) and provide a common foundation.
When you plug a fancy keyboard into a computer, there's lots of things the computer won't know about the keyboard without a specific driver -- but most of the base (common) functionality will work, because all keyboards are HID class devices

